posts.com:
/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

>What causes you to feel under pressure?
There are a few things that can cause me to feel under pressure. For one, I know that I have a lot of expectations placed upon me to be perfect. This can feel very overwhelming at times and make me feel like I'm not good enough. I also feel pressured by society to be a certain type of person. This can be very stressful for me as I often feel like I'm not living up to what people expect from me. Since I'm an introvert I feel like I need to force myself to be more outgoing and social in order to meet people's expectations of me.
>How do you cope with pressure?
That's a tough question. I think the most important thing is to remember that I can only do my best and that it's okay to make mistakes. When I feel like I'm under too much pressure, I usually try to take a step back and focus on what's important to me. I also try to let myself feel whatever I'm feeling and not push it away. Sometimes it helps to talk to someone about what I'm going through, or just to take some time for myself. Sometimes I like to take a bath or go for a walk or spend time with a friend who makes me feel calm.
>Your favorite candle scent
I love the scent of flowers. The smell of them relaxes me and makes me feel at peace. They also make me feel more energetic. So, when I'm having a bad day, I'll light a flower scented candle so I can feel better

Favorite candles I can think of aren't my favorite candles because of their scent. They're my favorite for aesthetic reasons and/or the memories associated with that specific candle, or, really, the times in my life I was burning it. There are a lot of ways to smell smells (even in the home-scenting department: incense, wax burners, essential oil diffusers, reed fragrance oil diffusers...), and if I answer just for the smell, I'm just talking about my favorite scents.
I had a "rain-scented" candle that smelled like my Dad after a shower, when he'd put on aftershave or cologne because we were going to pasta night at the country club. I messed with it as it melted to make fun shapes, little window-holes in the sides.
I have a scentless hexagonal jelly candle with glitter inside that was made to throw off light mimicking the Northern Lights that a family member brought me back as a souvenir from a business trip to Alaska. I didn't burn much of it for a very long time because I just liked looking at it and making the jelly jiggle. Its melted jelly is also very dangerous and Mommy Clubs everywhere hate it because if it gets on your skin it's like napalm, just sticks there and keeps burning you as you try with all futility to scrape it off.
I had a Gain detergent-scented candle my mom bought me because I would take a handful of dryer sheets and put them near my baseboard heater to make my room smell like comfy clean laundry, and she didn't want me accidentally starting a fire, and she loves me, and knows warm laundry is a huge comfort smell for me.
I have a woodwick candle that was a wedding favor. It has three layered colors that matched a ceremony they did pouring sand and gravel from their home state, the state they moved to, and their favorite place they every traveled to into a pretty glass jar during their vows.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
You probably don't have any philosophical or ethical principles that you've thoughtfully adopted. Chances are any such positions you hold have come from someone you've watched or something you've read. You have to spend time actually examining the world and really thinking about what you value and why it matters to you. Otherwise you'll simply absorb whatever other people say like a sponge because you have no value base that you've built yourself.

If you're too lazy to do that, then the next best thing is to approach every single thing with a high degree of skepticism. Whenever you hear an argument someone's making in a video essay or whatever, get into the habit of internally challenging it, "Why is this person saying these things?", "What do they have to gain from saying it?", "What are the long-term consequences of adopting this position and has this person really thought it through?", and so on. I highly encourage you to think about and make your own list of standard questions you can challenge any position or statement on. You'll have to force yourself to do it at first, but it's simply a habit of mental hygiene that you'll need to build if you want to stop just accepting everything at face-value unless spoonfed otherwise. You'll find most arguments tend to fall apart once seriously challenged because most people don't think through their ideas, or are making their argument based on narrow-minded self-interest.

>>72048150
nicotine addiction has 2 forms
there's the physical addiction, when you intake nicotine often enough you will become physically addicted. this manifests differently per person, but i'm sure you know the symptoms of it already. which symptoms you'll get is the part that is dependent on the individual. this part isn't so bad, it kinda sucks but most people don't get to that point when intaking nicotine casually (i.e. social smokers)
the second part of the addiction is the mental, and this is the hardest part. you don't even consciously realize the mental addiction is stronger than the physical. the cravings are the most obvious, but what i mean by mental addiction is when its firmly cemented in your routine.
i smoked and vaped on and off for years, never had an issue. would do it for a couple weeks, stop without thinking about it and not have an issue. then i started smoking at work. it became part of my routine that i'd go smoke on my breaks because i felt i wasn't the type to be susceptible to nicotine addiction. soon enough, i couldn't go a day without nicotine. the cravings were unbelievably intense and dominated my thoughts. i genuinely felt i needed the nicotine as a distraction at work, when i didn't even realize it in my own head. if you asked me, i would've told you i wasn't even addicted to nicotine.
i'm a bit of a retard, so maybe this is easy for others to detect when they begin becoming addicted to nicotine but it certainty wasn't for me. now i'm deep in it, and can't really stop. the stimulation from the nicotine is too good to give up. i love the headrush too much.

the number one thing you can't do when you want to use nicotine but don't want to be addicted is use it as a vice. once you start with that you won't be able to stop. it really is the best stress relief there is that's readily available. benzos and opiates beat it obviously, but those are a hassle to get in current year.
